source: ## 1.Introduction of Data Set

The dataset has 16 variables and 48858*16 observations including catagorical variables and numerical variables.
Catagorical variables:ID/name/host_id/host_name/neighbourhood_group/neighbourhood/room_type/last_review
Numerical variables:latitude/longitude/Price/numbers of reviews/reviews_per_month/calculated_host_listings_count/availability_365/minimum_nights This data mainly tells us about the daily price, relevant information and requirements of different kinds of rooms in some neighbourhood. Every host has different relevant id. There are some kinds of rooms in different neighbourhood including private room, entire room, shared room and so on.
According to the data analysis of this dataset we can address tree following problems:
1.What's the mean price of different neighbourhood group?
2.What's the mean value of minimum_nights between different kinds of rooms?
3.what's the number of availability in 356 days in Manhattan where the latitute is greater than 40.8 and the longitude is less than -73.9?

## 3.Data Visualization
### 3.1 some numerical descriptive statistics visualization

ax=plt.subplot()
ax.boxplot(df['price'])
ax.set_ylabel('Price')
plt.show()

This box plot shows the distribution of prices for listings. From the boxplot of price in all hosts, apparently we can see that there are lots of outliers. However, most of rooms's price are below 500 roughly belong to a normal range. We can know that the most expensive room's price is around 10000. From previous results we also know that the Q1, Q2, Q3 are seperately 69, 106, 175.

reviews_per_month=df['reviews_per_month']
plt.plot(reviews_per_month,marker = 'o', linestyle = '--')
plt.xlabel('different hosts')
plt.ylabel('reviews_per_month')
plt.title('reviews of different hosts monthly')
plt.show()

From this plot, we can tell that most of different hosts could get some reveiws every month from several reviews to roughly 20 reviews. And there is a host that might be so popular or have lots of customers that it got almost 60 reviews per month.

ax=plt.subplot()
ax.hist(df['calculated_host_listings_count'],bins=100)
ax.set_xlabel('calculated_host_listings_count')
ax.set_ylabel('hosts')
ax.set_title('calculated count provided by hosts_histogram1')
plt.show()

This histogram shows the distribution of the number of listings provided by different hosts. From this histogram1, we can know that it's right-skewed distribution. We can get that the mean is greater than the median from this feature. Plus, there are some outliers on the right.
Since the histogram1 is too sparse, then I will set a limit on X-axis to inspect some observation

ax=plt.subplot()
ax.hist(df['calculated_host_listings_count'],bins=350,alpha=0.5)
ax.set_xlabel('calculated_host_listings_count')
ax.set_ylabel('hosts')
ax.set_title('calculated count provided by hosts_histogram2')
ax.set_xlim([0,50])
plt.show()
From this histogram2, we can know that most of hosts only provide less than 10 count. It's still right-skewed distribution. We can get that the mean is greater than the median from this feature.

mean_minimum_nights=Bed_Breakfast.groupby('room_type')['minimum_nights'].mean()
print(mean_minimum_nights)
plt.plot(mean_minimum_nights,marker='o')
plt.xlabel('room_type')
plt.ylabel('minimum_nights')
plt.title('Mean minimum nights of different rooms')
plt.show()

Form this plot, we can see that there are three types of room.
We can tell that different rooms have a minimum nights requirement. The entire home has the highest requirements that customers need to book at least roughly 8 nights to get the room. On the contrary, the private room has the lowest requirements that customers need to book at least roughly 5 nights to get the room.
Then I want to take a look at the frequency of price by three type of rooms and I limited the price to 1000.

ax.set_title('price frequency of different type of rooms')
ax.legend()
ax.set_xlim([0,1000])

From the histogram, we can see that most of private rooms's price are roughly between 50-100.
Most of shared rooms's price are roughly between 50-150.
Most of entire rooms' price are roughly between 100-250.
There are some entire rooms that have outliers and the highest price reached 1000 roughly after we ignored the rooms that are more expensive.

The x-axis represents unique host IDs, while the y-axis represents the number of days a listing is available. From this scatter graph, we can see that the availability of rooms in Manhattan is spread from 0 to more than 350.
And different hosts in Manhattan have a spread availability every year. Therefore we can know that different hosts can provide different number of rooms to customers and the number is scatter.
## 4.Hypothesis Testing

### 4.1 Hypothesis Test1:
$\mu $ = the mean reviews per month in Manhattan
H0: $\mu = 10$
H1: $\mu \neq 10$
We assumed the population standard deviation σ is known.The sample size is large enough to claim the $\mu $ follow a normal distribution.
We choose to use z-test. The Formula:
$$ z=\frac{\bar{x}-\mu}{\sigma / \sqrt{n}}

from scipy import stats 
from statsmodels.stats.weightstats import ztest
review_monthly=Bed_Breakfast[Bed_Breakfast['neighbourhood_group']=='Manhattan']['reviews_per_month']
z_stat, p_value = ztest(review_monthly, value = 10)
print(f"Z-statistic: {z_stat:.4f}, p-value: {p_value:.4f}")
We set $\alpha = 0.05$. Given p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the mean reviews per month in Manhattan is significantly different from 10.

### 4.2 Hypothesis Test2:
two samples are independent, σ1 and σ2 are unknown but they are assumed to be equal.
μ1 = the mean price of private room
μ2 = the mean price of entire room.
$H_0: μ_1 = μ_2$ $\quad$ vs $\quad$ $H_1: μ_1 \neq μ_2$
The samples' size are large enough to claim the μ1 and μ2 follow a normal distribution.
We choose to use t-test. The Formula:
$$ t=\frac{(\bar{x_1}-\bar{x_2})-(\mu_1-\mu_2)}{s_{\bar{x_1}-\bar{x_2}}}

from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
price_privateroom=Bed_Breakfast[Bed_Breakfast['room_type']=='Private room']['price']
price_entireroom=Bed_Breakfast[Bed_Breakfast['room_type']=='Entire home/apt']['price']
tstat, pval = ttest_ind(price_privateroom,price_entireroom)
print(f"T-statistic: {tstat:.4f}, p-value: {pval:.4f}")
We set $\alpha = 0.05$. Given p-value is less than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the mean price of private room and entire room is significantly different.

from scipy.stats import levene
stat, p = levene(price_privateroom, price_entireroom)
print(f"Levene's Test: Statistic={stat:.4f}, p-value={p:.4f}")

We set $\alpha = 0.05$. Given p-value is less than 0.05,we reject the null hypothesis and conclude that the two populations don't have equal variance.
Then we need to use Welch's t-test. The Formula:
$$ \text{df}=\frac{\left(\cfrac{s_1^2}{n_1}+\cfrac{s_2^2}{n_2}\right)^2}{\cfrac{\left(\cfrac{s_1^2}{n_1}\right)^2}{n_1-1}+\cfrac{\left(\cfrac{s_2^2}{n_2}\right)^2}{n_2-1}} $$ $$ t=\frac{(\bar{x_1}-\bar{x_2})-(\mu_1-\mu_2)}{s_{\bar{x_1}-\bar{x_2}}}
tstat, pval = ttest_ind(price_privateroom, price_entireroom, equal_var = False)
print(f"Welch's t-test: {tstat:.4f}, p-value: {pval:.4f}")

We set $\alpha = 0.05$. From results, p-value is less than 0.05. It turns out that the results are identical with plain t-test. This maybe due to that the sample size is large enough ($n_p = n_e$ in this example is more than 40000) so the difference between the two become minimal.
## 5.Role of Human and Generative AI

I seldomly used the generative AI and finished most parts of this report by myself.

When I got the dataset, I looked at the variables and got the main topic from those variables. At first, I have some confuse about some variables like "minimum_nights", then I googled the meaning of it and figured out the meaning of it from original data sourses. After knowing the dataset, I thought about what important information we can get through the data analysis by Python. Therefore,I picked up three questions.

I reviewed the codes from previous notes and lectures. I got some useful methods to illustrate the sample mean, standard deviation, median, mode and my answer of previous three questions. Then I wrote down the relevant code and visualized the results by myself.

When I was visualizing the results, I found that there were some different methods to illustrate the different plots. And some plots' output didn't show well then I needed to change some parameters of them to show the graphs more clearly.For example, when I ploted the histogram I needed to change the "bins" to show a more better graph. 

At hypothesis testing part, I read some notes about how to conduct hypothesis testing. Then I reviewed the variables and observasions again and figured out which hypothesis I want to test and found the method to solve them. After designing those hypothesis, I found that some formulas were hard to present. Then I asked AI for help. From the AI's output, I kind of know how to edit the formulas in Markdown. But I also googled some methods to teach me how to present the formula by Markdown.
